{"key":"post-12784144","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12784144</id>\n<content>I'd toss it out.&amp;nbsp; I found a higher contamination rate once the grains start to smell rancid, even though they were boiled first, and then autoclaved at 20 psi for 90 minutes.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I did some microscopy and found that many of the bacteria were forming new endospores within hours of germinating.&amp;nbsp; I've since reduced my soak times to under 24 hours, and if it's rancid, down the toilet it goes.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;bootedboy said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;They will begin to sprout at this point, not just germinate.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;They won't sprout if you do the initial rinse and begin the soak in scalding hot tap water.&amp;nbsp; The heat 'pasteurizes' the grains, preventing germination during the soak.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12784198</next>\n<prev>12784136</prev>\n<first>12784121</first>\n<last>12784263</last>\n<when>1277228836</when>\n<utime>06/22/10 08:47 PM</utime>\n</post>"}